# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: donát-bánki
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The website has come under scrutiny from many governments starting in the late 2010s, including bans in China and Russia and in 2025 U.S.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed a domain registrar to identify the owner of archive.today's domain name.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] archive.today was founded in 2012 as a web archive.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] It allegedly registered its trademark in the Czech Republic in 2013.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The site originally branded itself as archive.today, but changed the primary mirror to archive.is in May 2015.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] It began to deprecate the archive.is domain in favor of other mirrors in January 2019.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] According to the archive.today blog, the website had saved about 500 million pages by 2021, 700 terabytes in total size.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In July 2013, archive.today began supporting the API of the Memento Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Due to budget constraints at LANL, the Memento Project was disestablished in September 2025.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Archive.today was one of the last major active users of the Memento protocol following the project's downsizing.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The closure of the Memento infrastructure at LANL in September 2025 came amid a broader period of increased scrutiny for the service.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Individual profile pages on 200.zona.media link to snapshots of social media posts by relatives, obituaries in local media, and other open-source evidence used to verify each death.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In early 2023, a team of researchers at the University of Amsterdam identified archive.today as the most-used open-access archiving service among fact-checking organisations, based on the European Digital Media Observatory's dataset on the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On 5 August 2023, Jani Patokallio published on his blog *Gyrovague* an investigation regarding archive.today's funding sources and the founder's identity.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On 30 October 2025, the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed archive.today's domain registrar, Tucows.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The subpoena stated its purpose was to identify the owner(s) of the archive.today domain name, and that it was part of a criminal investigation conducted by the FBI, the nature of which was not disclosed.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] News coverage of the subpoena mentioned Patokallio's report, where Patokallio has said there were "several indications" the founder was based in Russia.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In November 2025, the DNS provider AdGuard DNS reported that a French organization *Web Abuse Association Defense* (WAAD) had pressured it to block archive.today and its mirror domains.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] WAAD alleged that archive.today had refused to remove child sexual abuse material since 2023.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] When AdGuard contacted archive.today, the archive removed the material, stating that it had never received prior complaints about those URLs.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] AdGuard found WAAD suspicious as a recently registered association with minimal public presence, noting evidence of possible impersonation of a real French lawyer in similar WAAD complaints sent to other companies.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] AdGuard announced it would file a criminal complaint with French police.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On 14 January 2026, it emerged that archive.today had silently modified its CAPTCHA page to send repeated requests to *Gyrovague*, thereby causing visitors to unwittingly contribute to a DDOS attack against the blog.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The archive.today blog simultaneously posted several public criticisms of Patokallio.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Emails released by Patokallio show archive.today requesting the temporary removal of his report and later threatening him with AI pornography.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The community's decision was made despite concerns over maintaining content verifiability—partly undermined by the discovery of the alterations— while removing and replacing the second-largest archiving service used across the Wikimedia Foundation's projects.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The Wikimedia Foundation had stated its readiness to take action regardless of the community verdict.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Patokallio expressed his satisfaction with the outcome.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] This was not the first time Wikipedia had restricted links to archive.today.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In 2013, the community blacklisted archive.is, citing concerns about botnets, linkspamming, and the opaque manner in which the site was operated.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The decision was overturned in 2016 following a new request for comment, and archive.today was removed from the spam blacklist.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] At the time of the 2026 ban, the site was the second-largest archiving service used across all Wikimedia Foundation projects, with over 695,000 links spread across approximately 400,000 pages.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] archive.today can capture individual pages in response to explicit user requests.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Since its beginning, it has supported crawling pages with URLs containing the now-deprecated hash-bang fragment (#!).
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The website records only text and images, excluding XML, RTF, spreadsheet (xls or ods) and other non-static content.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] However, videos for certain sites, like Twitter, are saved.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] It keeps track of the history of snapshots saved, requesting confirmation before adding a new snapshot of an already saved page.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Once a web page is archived, it cannot be deleted directly by any Internet user.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Pages are captured at a browser width of 1,024 pixels.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] CSS is converted to inline CSS, removing responsive web design and selectors such as `:hover` and `:active`.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Content generated using JavaScript during the crawling process appears in a frozen state.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] HTML class names are preserved inside the `old-class` attribute.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] When text is selected, a JavaScript applet generates a URL fragment seen in the browser's address bar that automatically highlights that portion of the text when visited again.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Web pages can be duplicated from archive.today to web.archive.org as second-level backup, but archive.today does not save its snapshots in WARC format.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The reverse—from web.archive.org to archive.today—is also possible, but the copy usually takes more time than a direct capture.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] While saving a page, a list of URLs for individual page elements and their content sizes, HTTP statuses and MIME types is shown.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] This list can only be viewed during the crawling process.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Removing advertisements, popups or expanding links from archived pages is possible by asking the owner to do it on his blog.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] According to the site's FAQ, archive.today's storage layer runs on Apache Hadoop and Apache Accumulo, with all data stored on the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Textual content is replicated three times across servers in two data centers, both located in Europe, with at least one hosted by the French provider OVH; images are replicated twice.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The site does not store snapshots in WARC format.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The scraping component has used a modified version of the Chromium browser since November 2019, replacing the previous PhantomJS-based engine.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The research toolbar enables advanced keywords operators, using `*` as the wildcard character.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Paired quotation marks address the search to an exact sequence of keywords present in the title or in the body of the webpage, whereas the *insite* operator restricts it to a specific Internet domain.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] While saving a dynamic list, archive.today search box shows only a result that links the previous and the following section of the list (e.g.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The other web pages saved are filtered, and sometimes may be found by one of their occurrences.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The search feature is backed by Google CustomSearch.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] If it delivers no results, archive.today attempts to utilize Yandex Search.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] archive.today is frequently used to bypass paywalls on news websites, similarly to the defunct service 12ft.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The practice of sharing archive.today links to circumvent paywalls has sparked legal and ethical debate in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In the Netherlands, journalist Peter Aanzee publicly challenged a physician who shared an archive.ph link to one of his paywalled articles in *De Volkskrant*, arguing that distributing archived copies constituted copyright infringement.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Commentators have contrasted archive.today with the Internet Archive's Wayback Machine.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The same paywalled *Volkskrant* article shared via archive.ph was also found archived in the Wayback Machine, demonstrating that both services can be used to circumvent paywalls.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Like the Wayback Machine, archive.today does not advertise paywall circumvention among its stated features; the ability to bypass paywalls is a byproduct of its core function of archiving web pages as they appear to visitors.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] A 2025 investigation by journalist Henk van Ess found that AI chatbots—including ChatGPT, Perplexity AI, Grok, and Claude—exploit web archives to bypass paywalls during live web searches.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In one documented case, ChatGPT retrieved a full article from *The Economist* via archive.today and then generated a five-point economic analysis in the publication's characteristic style and terminology.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Van Ess identified six distinct methods of paywall circumvention by AI systems, of which "archive exploitation"—finding archived copies on services such as archive.today and the Internet Archive—was the most direct.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Unlike documented concerns about AI training unpaywalled content, this behaviour involves real-time retrieval through archived copies during individual queries, effectively extending paywall circumvention beyond human users to automated agents.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The researchers documented that archive.is URLs were extensively shared on "fringe" communities such as 4chan's /pol/ board and the Reddit subreddit r/The_Donald, both to preserve potentially contentious content and to deny ad revenue to news outlets perceived as ideologically opposed.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Moderation bots on r/The_Donald automatically blocked direct links to certain news sites—for example, 46% of links to the *New York Daily News* were censored—and prompted users to post archive.is URLs instead.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] The authors estimated that *The Washington Post* lost approximately US$70,000 per year in ad revenue due to the practice of sharing archived copies rather than direct links on Reddit alone.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On Reddit, bots were responsible for posting 44% of archive.is links and 85% of Wayback Machine links across the studied subreddits, driven by moderators aiming to mitigate link rot.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] A 2023 study by researchers at the University of Amsterdam, as part of the vera.ai project, examined 1,991 fact-checking articles from the European Digital Media Observatory's "War in Ukraine" dataset.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Of 41,758 extracted links, 6,002 were archived pages. archive.today was the most-used link archiving service, at 44.1%, ahead of the Internet Archive/Wayback Machine (29.2%) and Perma.cc (26.6%).
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Fact-checkers primarily used these services to preserve ephemeral and platform-restricted content, such as Facebook posts that are difficult to capture due to anti-bot measures.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In March 2019, the site was blocked for six months by several internet providers in Australia and New Zealand in the aftermath of the Christchurch mosque shootings in an attempt to limit distribution of the footage of the attack.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] According to GreatFire.org, archive.today has been blocked in mainland China since March 2016, archive.li since September 2017, archive.fo since July 2018, as well as archive.ph since December 2019.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On 21 July 2015, the archive.today blocked access to the service from all Finnish IP addresses, stating on Twitter that they did this in order to avoid escalating a dispute they allegedly had with the Finnish government.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] Since the conflict with the Finnish blogger in early 2026, the website displays an unpassable captcha to visitors from Finland.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] In 2016, the Russian communications agency Roskomnadzor began blocking access to archive.is from Russia.
[src:donát-bánki/archive-today] On 23 March 2026, archive.today and several mirror domains were blocked by Russian authorities.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The **Austrian Empire**, officially known as the **Empire of Austria**, was a multinational European great power from 1804 to 1867, created by proclamation out of the realms of the Habsburgs.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] During its existence, it was the third most populous nation in Europe after the Russian Empire and the United Kingdom, while geographically, it was the third-largest empire in Europe after the Russian Empire and the First French Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The empire was proclaimed by Francis II in 1804 in response to Napoleon's declaration of the First French Empire, unifying all Habsburg possessions under one central government.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] It remained part of the Holy Roman Empire until the latter's dissolution in 1806.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] It continued fighting against Napoleon throughout the Napoleonic Wars, except for a period between 1809 and 1813, when Austria was first allied with Napoleon during the invasion of Russia and later neutral during the first few weeks of the Sixth Coalition War.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Austria and its allies emerged victorious in the war, leading to the Congress of Vienna, which reaffirmed the empire as one of the great powers of the 19th century.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Kingdom of Hungary—as Regnum Independens—was administered by its own institutions separately from the rest of the empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] After Austria was defeated in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 was adopted, joining the Kingdom of Hungary and the Empire of Austria to form Austria-Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The background of the Austrian Empire is deeply rooted in the gradual rise and consolidation of the Habsburg monarchy, which developed over centuries as one of Europe's most powerful and enduring dynastic systems.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] By the 16th century, they controlled not only the Austrian hereditary lands but also territories such as Bohemia and Hungary, forming a loose but extensive composite monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Rather than being a unified state, the Habsburg monarchy functioned as a collection of distinct regions, each with its own laws, elites, and traditions, all held together by loyalty to the ruling dynasty.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This structure made governance complex, especially as the monarchy encompassed a wide range of ethnic groups, languages, and religions.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Habsburgs also became deeply tied to the Holy Roman Empire, with many of its rulers serving as emperors for centuries.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Religious conflict and external threats further shaped the monarchy's development.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] During the Reformation and Counter-Reformation, the Habsburgs positioned themselves as staunch defenders of Catholicism, which influenced both domestic policies and international alliances.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] At the same time, they faced persistent military pressure from the Ottoman Empire, particularly in Hungary and the Balkans.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] These conflicts pushed the monarchy toward greater centralization and military reform, especially from the 17th century onward.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] By the 18th century, under rulers like Maria Theresa and Joseph II, the monarchy underwent significant administrative and institutional changes.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] These reforms aimed to strengthen central authority, modernize the state, and improve efficiency, though they often met resistance from local elites.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Despite these efforts, the monarchy remained a patchwork of territories rather than a cohesive nation.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This long dynastic, multi-ethnic, and decentralized background is what ultimately gave shape to the Austrian Empire in 1804.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The empire was less a new creation and more a formal rebranding of the Habsburg Monarchy under changing geopolitical pressures, especially in response to the transformations brought by Napoleon.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Changes shaping the nature of the Holy Roman Empire took place during conferences in Rastatt (1797–1799) and Regensburg (1801–1803).
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] On 24 March 1803, the Imperial Recess (German: *Reichsdeputationshauptschluss*) was declared, which reduced the number of ecclesiastical states from 81 to only 3 and the free imperial cities from 51 to 6.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Taking this significant change into consideration, Holy Roman Emperor Francis II created the title Emperor of Austria for himself and his successors, thereby becoming Francis I of Austria.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Initially Francis II/I continued to hold both titles but abdicated the throne of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] '*Kaiser*-dom') comprised all the lands of the Habsburg monarchy, which had until then been legally separate realms in personal union (a composite monarchy) under Francis and his predecessors.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] By contrast, the Austrian Empire was legally a single state, although the overarching structure and the status of its component lands at first stayed much the same as they had been under the composite monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Hungary's affairs remained administered by its own institutions (King and Diet) as they had been beforehand; thus no Imperial institutions were involved in its government.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The fall and dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire was accelerated by French intervention in the Empire in 1805, with the French defeating Austrian armies at Ulm and Austerlitz, forcing an Austrian-French armistice on 6 December 1806.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian losses encouraged rulers of imperial territories to ally with the French, receive higher titles and assert formal independence in the following days, such as Maximilian IV Joseph of Bavaria, Frederick III of Württemberg and Charles Frederick of Baden.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Francis II agreed to the humiliating Treaty of Pressburg which recognised the rulers' new titles and ceded large territories to Napoleon's German allies and the French satellite Italy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In practice this meant the dissolution of the long-lived Holy Roman Empire and a reorganization under a Napoleonic model of the German states.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Austrian claims on those German states were renounced without exception.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] On 12 July 1806, the Confederation of the Rhine was established, comprising 16 sovereigns and countries under French influence, *de facto* put an end to the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] On 6 August 1806, Francis proclaimed the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire, as he did not want Napoleon to succeed him.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] His claims were later settled by the creation of the Kingdom of Hanover which was held by George IV and William IV as Kings of Hanover.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Succession could only be in the male line, so on Queen Victoria's accession to the British throne, her uncle, Ernest Augustus, succeeded as King of Hanover, thus ending the personal union with Great Britain that dated to 1714.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Klemens von Metternich became Foreign Minister in 1809.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] He also held the post of Chancellor of State from 1821 until 1848, under both Francis I and his son Ferdinand I.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The period of 1815–1848 is also referred to as the "Age of Metternich", with Metternich controlling the Habsburg monarchy's foreign policy and having a major influence in European politics.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] He was known for his strong conservative views and approach in politics, with policies strongly against revolution and liberalism.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In his opinion, liberalism was a form of legalized revolution.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich believed that absolute monarchy was the only proper system of government.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This notion influenced his anti-revolutionary policy to ensure the continuation of the Habsburg monarchy in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich was a practitioner of balance-of-power diplomacy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] His foreign policy aimed to maintain international political equilibrium to preserve the Habsburgs' power and influence in international affairs.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Following the Napoleonic Wars, Metternich was the chief architect of the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire was the main beneficiary from the Congress of Vienna and it established an alliance with Britain, Prussia, and Russia forming the Quadruple Alliance.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire also gained new territories from the Congress of Vienna, and its influence expanded to the north through the German Confederation and also into Italy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Due to the Congress of Vienna in 1815, Austria was the leading member of the German Confederation.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Following the Congress, the major European powers agreed to meet and discuss resolutions in the event of future disputes or revolutions.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Because of Metternich's main role in the architecture of the Congress, these meetings are also referred to as the "Metternich congress" or "Metternich system".
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Under Metternich as the Austrian foreign minister, other congresses would meet to resolve European foreign affairs.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Metternich congresses aimed to maintain the political equilibrium among the European powers and prevent revolutionary efforts.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] These meetings also aimed to resolve foreign issues and disputes without resorting to violence.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] By means of these meetings and by allying the Austrian Empire with other European powers whose monarchs had a similar interest in preserving conservative political direction, Metternich was able to establish the Austrian Empire's influence on European politics.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Also, because Metternich used the fear of revolutions among European powers, which he also shared, he was able to establish security and predominance of the Habsburgs in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Under Metternich, nationalist revolts in Austrian north Italy and in the German states were forcibly crushed.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] At home, he pursued a similar policy to suppress revolutionary and liberal ideals.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] He employed the Carlsbad Decrees of 1819, which used strict censorship of education, press and speech to repress revolutionary and liberal concepts.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich also used a wide-ranging spy network to dampen down unrest.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich operated very freely with regard to foreign policy under Emperor Francis I's reign.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This date marks the decline of Metternich's influence in the Austrian Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Francis' heir was his son Ferdinand I, but he suffered from health issues.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Ferdinand's accession preserved the Habsburg dynastic succession, but he was not capable of ruling.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The leadership of the Austrian Empire was transferred to a state council composed of Metternich, Francis I's brother Archduke Louis, and Count Franz Anton Kolowrat, who later became the first Minister-President of the Austrian Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The liberal Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire forced Metternich's resignation.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich is remembered for his success in maintaining the status quo and the Habsburg influence in international affairs.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] No Habsburg foreign minister following Metternich held a similar position within the empire for such a long time nor held such a vast influence on European foreign affairs.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Historians generally consider the Metternich era as a period of stability: the Austrian Empire fought no wars nor did it undergo any radical internal reforms.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] However, it was also thought of as a period of economic growth and prosperity in the Austrian Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The population of Austria rose to 37.5 million by 1843.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Urban expansion also occurred and the population of Vienna reached 400,000.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] During the Metternich era, the Austrian Empire also maintained a stable economy and reached an almost balanced budget, despite having a major deficit following the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] From March 1848 through November 1849, the Empire was threatened by revolutionary movements, most of which were of a nationalist character.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Besides that, liberal and even socialist currents resisted the empire's longstanding conservatism.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Although most of the revolution plans failed, some changes were made; significant lasting reforms included the abolition of serfdom, cancellation of censorship and a promise made by Ferdinand I of Austria said to implement a constitution throughout the whole Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] After the death of Prince Felix of Schwarzenberg in 1852, the Minister of the Interior Baron Alexander von Bach largely dictated policy in Austria and Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Bach centralized administrative authority for the Austrian Empire, but he also endorsed reactionary policies that reduced freedom of the press and abandoned public trials.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] He later represented the Absolutist (or *Klerikalabsolutist*) party, which culminated in the concordat of August 1855 that gave the Roman Catholic Church control over education and family life.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This period in the history of the Austrian Empire would become known as the era of neo-absolutism, or Bach's absolutism.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The pillars of the so-called Bach system (*Bachsches System*) were, in the words of Adolf Fischhof, four "armies": *a standing army of soldiers, a sitting army of office holders, a kneeling army of priests and a fawning army of sneaks*.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Prisons were full of political prisoners, like Czech nationalist journalist and writer Karel Havlíček Borovský who was forcibly expatriated (1851–1855) to Brixen.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This exile undermined Borovský's health and he died soon afterwards.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This affair earned Bach a very bad reputation among Czechs and subsequently led to the strengthening of the Czech national movement.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] However, Bach's relaxed ideological views (apart from the neo-absolutism) led to a great rise in the 1850s of economic freedom.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Internal customs duties were abolished, and peasants were emancipated from their feudal obligations.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In its capacity as leader of the German Confederation, Austria participated with volunteers in the First War of Schleswig (1848–1850).
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Sardinia allied itself with France for the conquest of Lombardy–Venetia.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Austria was defeated in the 1859 armed conflict.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Treaties of Villafranca and Zürich removed Lombardy, except for the part east of the Mincio river, the so-called Mantovano.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Constitution of 1861 (the "February Patent") created a House of Lords (*Herrenhaus*) and a House of Deputies (*Abgeordnetenhaus*).
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] But most nationalities of the monarchy remained dissatisfied.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] After the second war with Denmark in 1864, Holstein came under Austrian administration, and Schleswig and Lauenburg under Prussian administration.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] But the internal difficulties continued.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Diets replaced the parliament in 17 provinces, the Hungarians pressed for autonomy, and Venetia was attracted by the now unified Italy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] After the Austrian army was defeated in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866 and the German Confederation was dissolved, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 was adopted.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] By this act, the Kingdom of Hungary and the Empire of Austria as two separate entities joined on an equal basis to form the Dual Monarchy of Austria-Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Napoleonic Wars dominated Austrian foreign policy from 1804 to 1815.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian army was one of the most formidable forces the French had to face.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] After Prussia signed a peace treaty with France on 5 April 1795, Austria was forced to carry the main burden of war with Napoleonic France for almost ten years.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This severely overburdened the Austrian economy, making the war greatly unpopular.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Emperor Francis I therefore refused to join any further war against Napoleon for a long time.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] On the other hand, Francis I continued to intrigue for the possibility of revenge against France, entering into a secret military agreement with the Russian Empire in November 1804.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] This convention was to assure mutual cooperation in the case of a new war against France.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Austrian unwillingness to join the Third Coalition was overcome by British subsidies, but the Austrians withdrew from the war yet again after a decisive defeat at the Battle of Austerlitz.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Although the Austrian budget suffered from wartime expenditures and its international position was significantly undermined, the humiliating Treaty of Pressburg provided plenty of time to strengthen the army and economy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Moreover, the ambitious Archduke Charles and Johann Philipp von Stadion never abandoned the goal of further war with France.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Archduke Charles of Austria served as the Head of the Council of War and Commander in Chief of the Austrian army.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Endowed with the enlarged powers, he reformed the Austrian Army to preparedness for another war.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Johann Philipp von Stadion, the foreign minister, personally hated Napoleon due to an experience of confiscation of his possessions in France by Napoleon.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In addition, the third wife of Francis I, Maria Ludovika of Austria-Este, agreed with Stadion's efforts to begin a new war.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Klemens Wenzel von Metternich, located in Paris, called for careful advance in the case of the war against France.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The defeat of French army at the Battle of Bailén in Spain on 27 July 1808 triggered the war.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] On 9 April 1809, an Austrian force of 170,000 men attacked Bavaria.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] It participated in a second invasion of France in 1815, and put an end to Murat's regime in south Italy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The latter period of Napoleonic Wars featured Metternich exerting a large degree of influence over foreign policy in the Austrian Empire, a matter nominally decided by the Emperor.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich initially supported an alliance with France, arranging the marriage between Napoleon and Francis I's daughter, Marie-Louise; however, by the 1812 campaign, he had realised the inevitability of Napoleon's downfall and took Austria to war against France.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Metternich's influence at the Congress of Vienna was remarkable, and he became not only the premier statesman in Europe but the virtual ruler of the Empire until 1848—the Year of revolutions—and the rise of liberalism equated to his political downfall.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The result was that the Austrian Empire was seen as one of the great powers after 1815, but also as a reactionary force and an obstacle to national aspirations in Italy and Germany.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] During this time, Metternich was able to maintain an elaborate balance between Prussia, the lesser German states, and Austria in the German Confederation.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Thanks to his efforts, Austria was seen as the senior partner with Prussia keeping watch over Germany as a whole.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Further, Metternich opposed the weakening of France in the years after Napoleon, and viewed the new monarchy in Paris as an effective tool in keeping Russia at bay.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] From 1815 to 1848, Metternich steered Austria Imperial foreign policy, and indeed the mood of Europe, and managed to keep peace on the continent despite the growing liberal and radical movements inside most major powers.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] His resignation in 1848, forced by moderates in the court, and revolutionaries in the streets, may have caused the spread of the revolutions throughout the monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] It is stipulated that Metternich's departure emboldened liberal factions in Austria and Hungary, but this cannot be confirmed for certain.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] During the Crimean War, Austria maintained a policy of hostile neutrality towards Russia, and, while not going to war, was supportive of the Anglo-French coalition.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The old Habsburg possessions of Further Austria (in today's France, Germany and Switzerland) had already been lost in the 1805 Peace of Pressburg.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] From 1850, Croatia, Slavonia, and the Military Frontier constituted a single land with disaggregated provincial and military administration, and representation.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Administratively, most of the crown lands excluding Hungary, Croatia, Slavonia, Transylvania, Lombardy–Venetia and the Military Frontier were divided into *Kreise* ('circles'), an administrative division introduced under Maria Theresa in the 18th century.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In the course of the post-1848 reforms Transylvania was also divided into *Kreise* in 1851 (re-divided in 1854); the Voivodeship of Serbia and Banat of Temeschwar was also divided into *Kreise*.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] German was the primary language of higher education in the empire.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian foreign trade was one-third of that of France and one-fifth of Great Britain based on 1823–37 numbers.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Austrian Empire was multi-national and multi-ethnic, with Germans, Hungarians (constituent in the Kingdom of Hungary), Slavs (Czechs, Poles, Ruthenians, Croats, Slovaks, Serbs, Slovenes) and Romanians, with smaller numbers of other ethnic groups.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Becher's statistics, the population number was 36,950,401 in 1840.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Slavs made up an estimated 16 million, roughly 12 million north of the Danube and 4 million south of it.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Germans made up an estimated 6,5 million, of which 3 million in Upper and Lower Austria, Tyrol and one-half of Styra, and the rest scattered in the other provinces.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Hungarians made up an estimated 5,5 million.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Italians made up an estimated 4,6 million, in Lombardy, Venice, south Tyrol, and south Illyria.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] Wallachians made up an estimated 1,560,000 in Hungary and Transylvania.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] In the mid-19th-century ethnographic works used the term *nationalität* (nationality) as a synonym for *volk* (ethnic group).
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The various terms used for the peoples of the monarchy were *Nation*, *Volk*, *Völkerschaft* and derivations *Volkstamm*, *Volksgruppe*.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] The Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire included the minorities choosing sides between revolution against the monarchy or supporting the monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/austrian-empire] When Hungary revolted, the kingdom's Croats, Serbs and Romanians supported the monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:donát-bánki/automobiles] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:donát-bánki/bakonybánk] In the 19th and 20th centuries, a small Jewish community lived in the village (in 1880 61 Jews lived in the village).
[src:donát-bánki/bakonybánk] However, most of the village's Jews were murdered in the Holocaust.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is a global city, consistently ranked among the 50 most important cities in the world, belongs to the narrow group of cities with a GDP over US$120 billion, was named a global cultural capital as having high-quality human capital, and is among the 35 most liveable cities in the world.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest also hosts various international organizations, including several UN agencies, the WHO Budapest Centre, IOM regional centre, the EU headquarters of EIT and CEPOL, as well as the first foreign office of China Investment Agency.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The history of Budapest began with an early Celtic settlement transformed by the Romans into the town of Aquincum, capital of Lower Pannonia in the 1st century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Following the foundation of Hungary in the late 9th century, the area was pillaged by the Mongols in 1241.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] It became the royal seat in 1361, with Buda becoming one of the European centers of renaissance culture by the 15th century under Matthias Corvinus.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The siege of Buda in 1541 was followed by nearly 150 years of Ottoman rule, and after the reconquest of Buda in 1686, the region entered a new age of prosperity, with Pest-Buda becoming a global city after the unification of Buda, Pest and Óbuda in 1873.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] By this time, Budapest had become the co-capital of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, a great power that dissolved in 1918 following World War I.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city was also the focal point of the Hungarian Revolution of 1848, Battle of Budapest in 1945, and Hungarian Revolution of 1956.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest has been a popular spa destination since Roman times and is considered the spa capital of Europe, with more than 100 medicinal geothermal springs and the largest thermal water cave system.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city is home to the second-largest synagogue and third-largest parliament building in the world, over 40 museums and galleries, nearly ten Michelin-starred restaurants, and named among the 50 best food cities globally for its focus on distinctive Hungarian cuisine.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is also renowned for its nightlife, with ruin bars playing a significant role in it; moreover, the city has become a center for Hollywood film production in recent years.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city also hosted the 2023 World Athletics Championships and the 2017 and 2022 World Aquatics Championships.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest attracted 7 million international overnight visitors in 2025, making it one of the most popular destinations in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The previously separate cities of Buda, Óbuda, and Pest were officially unified in 1873 and given the new name *Budapest*.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Before this, the towns together had sometimes been referred to colloquially as "Pest-Buda".
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] *Pest* is often used *pars pro toto* for the entire city in contemporary colloquial Hungarian, although it is also used to refer to all parts of the city east of the Danube.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Conversely, *Buda* colloquially means all districts to the Danube's west—including the former Óbuda.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Danube islands—including Csepel, the city's XXI. district—are part of neither Buda nor Pest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] All varieties of English pronounce the *-s-* as in the English word *pest*.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The *-u* in *Buda-* is pronounced either /u/ like *food* (as in US: /ˈbuːdəpɛst/) or /ju/ like *cue* (as in UK: /ˌb(j)uːdəˈpɛst/).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In Hungarian, the *-s-* is pronounced /ʃ/ as in *wash*; in IPA: Hungarian: [ˈbudɒpɛʃt] ⓘ.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The origins of the names "Buda" and "Pest" are obscure.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Linguistically, however, a German origin through the Slavic derivative вода (*voda*, water) is not possible, and there is no certainty that a Turkic word really comes from the word *buta* ~ *buda* 'branch, twig'.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] According to a legend recorded in chronicles from the Middle Ages, "Buda" comes from the name of its founder, Bleda, brother of Hunnic ruler Attila.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] One states that the name derives from Roman times, since there was a local fortress (Contra-Aquincum) called by Ptolemy "Pession" ("Πέσσιον", iii.7.§ 2).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Another has it that Pest originates in the Slavic word for cave, *пещера*, or *peštera*.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] A third cites *пещ*, or *pešt*, referencing a cave where fires burned or a limekiln.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The first settlement on the territory of Budapest was built by Celts before 1 AD.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Roman settlement – Aquincum – became the main city of Pannonia Inferior in 106 AD.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] At first, it was a military settlement, and gradually the city rose around it, making it the focal point of the city's commercial life.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Today, this area corresponds to the Óbuda district within Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Romans constructed roads, amphitheatres, baths and houses with heated floors in this fortified military camp.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Roman city of Aquincum is the best-conserved of the Roman sites in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The archaeological site was turned into a museum with indoor and open-air sections.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Meanwhile, settlement in the area east of the Danube, which was not part of the Roman Empire, remained Germanic and Sarmatian in character.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Research places the probable residence of the Árpáds as an early place of central power near what became Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Mongol invasion in the 13th century quickly proved it was difficult to defend a plain.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] King Béla IV of Hungary, therefore, ordered the construction of reinforced stone walls around the towns and set his own royal palace on the top of the protecting hills of Buda.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] German settlers were invited to rebuild and inhabit both Buda and Pest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1361 it became the capital of Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The cultural role of Buda was particularly significant during the reign of King Matthias Corvinus.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Italian Renaissance had a great influence on the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] His library, the Bibliotheca Corviniana, was Europe's greatest collection of historical chronicles and philosophic and scientific works in the 15th century, and second in size only to the Vatican Library.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After the foundation of the first Hungarian university in Pécs in 1367 (University of Pécs), the second one was established in Óbuda in 1395 (University of Óbuda).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The first Hungarian book was printed in Buda in 1473.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Buda had about 5,000 inhabitants around the year 1500.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Ottomans conquered Buda in 1526, as well as in 1529, and finally occupied it in 1541.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Ottoman Rule lasted for more than 150 years.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Ottoman Turks constructed many prominent bathing facilities within the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some of the baths that the Turks erected during their rule are still in use 500 years later, including Rudas Baths and Király Baths.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] By 1547 the number of Christians was down to about a thousand, and by 1647 it had fallen to only about seventy.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The unoccupied western part of the country became part of the Habsburg monarchy as Royal Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1686, two years after the unsuccessful siege of Buda, a renewed campaign was started to enter Buda.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This time, the Holy League's army was twice as large, containing over 74,000 men, including German, Croat, Dutch, Hungarian, English, Spanish, Czech, Italian, French, Burgundian, Danish and Swedish soldiers, along with other Europeans as volunteers, artillerymen, and officers.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Christian forces seized Buda, and in the next few years, all of the former Hungarian lands, except areas near Temesvár (Timișoara), were taken from the Turks.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the 1699 Treaty of Karlowitz, these territorial changes were officially recognized as the end of the rule of the Turks, and in 1718 the entire Kingdom of Hungary was removed from Ottoman rule.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The 19th century was dominated by the Hungarian struggle for independence and modernisation.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The national insurrection against the Habsburgs began in the Hungarian capital in 1848 and was defeated one and a half years later, with the help of the Russian Empire.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] 1867 was the year of Reconciliation that brought about the birth of Austria-Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This made Budapest the twin capital of a dual monarchy.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] It was this compromise which opened the second great phase of development in the history of Budapest, lasting until World War I.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1849, the Chain Bridge linking Buda with Pest was opened as the first permanent bridge across the Danube and in 1873 Buda and Pest were officially merged with the third part, Óbuda (Old Buda), thus creating the new metropolis of Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The dynamic Pest grew into the country's administrative, political, economic, trade and cultural hub.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Ethnic Hungarians overtook Germans in the second half of the 19th century due to mass migration from the overpopulated rural Transdanubia and Great Hungarian Plain.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Between 1851 and 1910 the proportion of Hungarians increased from 35.6% to 85.9%, Hungarian became the dominant language, and German was crowded out.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The proportion of Jews peaked in 1900 with 23.6%.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Due to the prosperity and the large Jewish community of the city at the start of the 20th century, Budapest was often called the "Jewish Mecca" or "Judapest".
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest also became an important centre for the Aromanian diaspora during the 19th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1918, Austria-Hungary lost the war and collapsed; Hungary declared itself an independent republic (Republic of Hungary).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] On the 4th of August, 1919, the Romanian Army occupied Budapest, marking the end of the Hungarian-Romanian War.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1920 the Treaty of Trianon partitioned the country, and as a result, Hungary lost over two-thirds of its territory, and about two-thirds of its inhabitants, including 3.3 million out of 15 million ethnic Hungarians.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1944, a year before the end of World War II, Budapest was partly destroyed by British and American air raids (first attack 4 April 1944).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] From 24 December 1944 to 13 February 1945, the city was besieged during the Battle of Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest sustained major damage caused by the attacking Soviet and Romanian troops and the defending German and Hungarian troops.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] More than 38,000 civilians died during the conflict.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] All bridges were destroyed by the Germans.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The stone lions that have decorated the Chain Bridge since 1852 survived the devastation of the war.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Between 20% and 40% of Greater Budapest's 250,000 Jewish inhabitants died through Nazi and Arrow Cross Party, during the German occupation of Hungary, from 1944 to early 1945.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Swiss diplomat Carl Lutz rescued tens of thousands of Jews by issuing Swiss protection papers and designating numerous buildings, including the now famous Glass House (Üvegház) at Vadász Street 29, to be Swiss protected territory.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] About 3,000 Hungarian Jews found refuge at the Glass House and in a neighbouring building.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg saved the lives of tens of thousands of Jews in Budapest by giving them Swedish protection papers and taking them under his consular protection.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Wallenberg was abducted by the Russians on 17 January 1945 and never regained freedom.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Giorgio Perlasca, an Italian citizen, saved thousands of Hungarian Jews posing as a Spanish diplomat.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some other diplomats also abandoned diplomatic protocol and rescued Jews.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] There are two monuments for Wallenberg, one for Carl Lutz and one for Giorgio Perlasca in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Following the capture of Hungary from Nazi Germany by the Red Army, Soviet military occupation ensued, which ended only in 1991.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Soviets exerted significant influence on Hungarian political affairs.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1949, Hungary was declared a communist People's Republic (People's Republic of Hungary).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The new Communist government considered the buildings like the Buda Castle symbols of the former regime, and during the 1950s the palace was gutted and all the interiors were destroyed (also see Stalin era).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] On 23 October 1956, citizens held a large peaceful demonstration in Budapest demanding democratic reform.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The demonstrators went to the Budapest radio station and demanded to publish their demands.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The regime ordered troops to shoot into the crowd.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Hungarian soldiers gave rifles to the demonstrators who were now able to capture the building.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This initiated the Hungarian Revolution of 1956.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The demonstrators demanded to appoint Imre Nagy to be Prime Minister of Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] To their surprise, the central committee of the "Hungarian Working People's Party" did so that same evening.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This uprising was an anti-Soviet revolt that lasted from 23 October until 11 November.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After Nagy had declared that Hungary was to leave the Warsaw Pact and become neutral, Soviet tanks and troops entered the country to crush the revolt.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Fighting continued until mid November, leaving more than 3000 dead.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] A monument was erected at the fiftieth anniversary of the revolt in 2006, at the edge of the City Park.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Its shape is a wedge with a 56 angle degree made in rusted iron that gradually becomes shiny, ending in an intersection to symbolize Hungarian forces that temporarily eradicated the Communist leadership.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] From the 1960s to the late 1980s, Hungary was often satirically referred to as "the happiest barrack" within the Eastern bloc, and much of the wartime damage to the city was finally repaired.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Work on Erzsébet Bridge, the last to be rebuilt, was finished in 1964.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the early 1970s, Budapest Metro's east–west M2 line was first opened, followed by the M3 line in 1976.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1987, Buda Castle and the banks of the Danube were included in the UNESCO list of World Heritage Sites.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Andrássy Avenue (including the Millennium Underground Railway, Hősök tere, and Városliget) was added to the UNESCO list in 2002.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the 1980s, the city's population reached 2.1 million.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In recent times a significant decrease in population occurred mainly due to a massive movement to the neighbouring agglomeration in Pest county, i.e., suburbanisation.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the last decades of the 20th century the political changes of 1989–90 (Fall of the Iron Curtain) concealed changes in civil society and along the streets of Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The monuments of the dictatorship were removed from public places, into Memento Park.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the first 20 years of the new democracy, the development of the city was managed by its mayor, Gábor Demszky.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In October 2019, opposition candidate Gergely Karácsony won the Budapest mayoral election, meaning the first electoral blow for Hungary's nationalist prime minister Viktor Orbán since coming to power in 2010.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest, strategically placed at the centre of the Pannonian Basin, lies on an ancient route linking the hills of Transdanubia with the Great Plain.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The 525-square-kilometre (203 sq mi) area of Budapest lies in Central Hungary, surrounded by settlements of the agglomeration in Pest county.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The capital extends 25 and 29 km (16 and 18 mi) in the north–south, east–west direction respectively.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Danube enters the city from the north; later it encircles two islands, Óbuda Island and Margaret Island.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The third island Csepel Island is the largest of the Budapest Danube islands, however only its northernmost tip is within city limits.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The river that separates the two parts of the city is 230 m (755 ft) wide at its narrowest point in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Pest lies on the flat terrain of the Great Plain while Buda is rather hilly.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The wide Danube was always fordable at this point because of a small number of islands in the middle of the river.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city has marked topographical contrasts: Buda is built on the higher river terraces and hills of the western side, while the considerably larger Pest spreads out on a flat and featureless sand plain on the river's opposite bank.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Pest's terrain rises with a slight eastward gradient, so the easternmost parts of the city lie at the same elevation as Buda's smallest hills, notably Gellért Hill and Castle Hill.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Buda hills consist mainly of limestone and dolomite, the water created speleothems, the most famous ones being the Pálvölgyi cave (total length 7,200 m or 23,600 ft) and the Szemlőhegyi cave (total length 2,200 m or 7,200 ft).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The hills were formed in the Triassic Period.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The highest point of the hills and of Budapest is János Hill, at 527 metres (1,729 feet) above sea level.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The lowest point is the line of the Danube which is 96 metres (315 feet) above sea level.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Of the 525 square kilometres (203 square miles) occupied by the city, 83 square kilometres (32 square miles) is green area, park and forest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The forests of Buda hills are environmentally protected.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city's importance in terms of traffic is very central, because many major European roads and European railway lines lead to Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Danube was and is still an important water-way and this region in the centre of the Carpathian Basin lies at the cross-roads of trade routes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is one of only three capital cities in the world which has thermal springs (the others being Reykjavík in Iceland and Sofia in Bulgaria).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some 125 springs produce 70 million litres (18 million US gallons) of thermal water a day, with temperatures ranging up to 58 °C.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some of these waters have been claimed to have medicinal effects due to their high mineral contents.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest has a transitional climate between a humid temperate climate (Köppen: *Cfa*, Trewartha: *Doak*), and a humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*, Trewartha: *Dcao*), with warm to hot summers and chilly winters.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Winter (November until early March) can be cold and the city receives little sunshine.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Snowfall is fairly frequent in most years, and nighttime temperatures of −10 °C (14 °F) are not uncommon between mid-December and mid-February.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The spring months (March and April) see variable conditions, with a rapid increase in the average temperature.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The weather in late March and in April is often very agreeable during the day and fresh at night.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest's long summer – lasting from May until mid-September – is warm or very warm.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Sudden heavy showers also occur, particularly in May and June.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The autumn in Budapest (mid-September until late October) is characterised by little rain and long sunny days with moderate temperatures.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Temperatures often turn abruptly colder in late October or early November.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Mean annual precipitation in Budapest is around 586 mm (23.1 in).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] On average, there are 84 days with precipitation and 1988 hours of sunshine (of a possible 4383) each year.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city lies on the boundary between Zone 6 and Zone 7 in terms of the hardiness zone.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest has architecturally noteworthy buildings in a wide range of styles and from distinct time periods, from the ancient times as Roman City of Aquincum in Óbuda (District III), which dates to around 89 AD, to the most modern Palace of Arts, the contemporary arts museum and concert hall.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Most buildings in Budapest are relatively low: in the early 2010s there were around 100 buildings higher than 45 metres (148 ft).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The number of high-rise buildings is kept low by building legislation, which is aimed at preserving the historic cityscape and to meet the requirements of the World Heritage Site.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Strong rules apply to the planning, authorisation and construction of high-rise buildings and consequently much of the inner city does not have any.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some planners would like to see an easing of the rules for the construction of skyscrapers, and the possibility of building skyscrapers outside the city's historic core has been raised.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the chronological order of architectural styles Budapest is represented on the entire timeline, starting with the Roman City of Aquincum representing ancient architecture.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The next determinative style is the Gothic architecture in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The few remaining Gothic buildings can be found in the Castle District.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] 18, 20 and 22 on Országház Street, which date back to the 14th century and No.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] 31 Úri Street, which has a Gothic façade that dates back to the 15th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Other buildings with Gothic features are the Inner City Parish Church, built in the 12th century, and the Mary Magdalene Church, completed in the 15th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The most characteristic Gothic-style buildings are actually Neo-Gothic, like the most well-known Budapest landmarks, the Hungarian Parliament Building and the Matthias Church, where much of the original material was used (originally built in Romanesque style in 1015).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The next chapter in the history of human architecture is Renaissance architecture.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] One of the earliest places to be influenced by the Renaissance style of architecture was Hungary, and Budapest in particular.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The style appeared following the marriage of King Matthias Corvinus and Beatrice of Naples in 1476.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Many Italian artists, craftsmen and masons came to Buda with the new queen.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Today, many of the original renaissance buildings disappeared during the varied history of Buda, but Budapest is still rich in renaissance and neo-renaissance buildings, like the famous Hungarian State Opera House, St.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Stephen's Basilica and the Hungarian Academy of Sciences.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] During the Turkish occupation (1541–1686), Islamic culture flourished in Budapest; multiple mosques and baths were built in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] These were great examples of Ottoman architecture, which was influenced by Muslims from around the world including Turkish, Iranian, Arabian and to a larger extent, Byzantine architecture as well as Islamic traditions.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After the Holy League conquered Budapest, they replaced most of the mosques with churches and minarets were turned into bell towers and cathedral spires.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] At one point the distinct sloping central square in Budapest became a bustling Oriental bazaar, which was filled with "the chatter of camel caravans on their way to Yemen and India".
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is in fact one of the few places in the world with functioning original Turkish bathhouses dating back to the 16th century, like Rudas Baths or Király Baths.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is home to the northernmost place where the tomb of influential Islamic Turkish Sufi Dervish, Gül Baba is found.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Various cultures converged in Hungary seemed to coalesce well with each other, as if all these different cultures and architecture styles are digested into Hungary's own way of cultural blend.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] A precedent to show the city's self-conscious is the top section of the city's main square, named as Szechenyi.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] When Turks came to the city, they built mosques here which was aggressively replaced with Gothic church of St.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The rationale of reusing the base of the former Islamic building mosque and reconstruction into Gothic Church but Islamic style architecture over it is typically Islamic are still visible.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] An official term for the rationale is spolia.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The mosque was called the djami of Pasha Gazi Kassim, and djami means congregational or Friday mosque in Arabic.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After Turks and Muslims were expelled and massacred from Budapest, the site was reoccupied by Christians and reformed into a church, the Inner City Parish Church (Budapest).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The minaret and Turkish entranceway were removed.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The shape of the architecture is its only hint of exotic past—"two surviving prayer niches facing Mecca and an ecumenical symbol atop its cupola: a cross rising above the Turkish crescent moon".
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After 1686, the Baroque architecture designated the dominant style of art in catholic countries from the 17th century to the 18th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] There are many Baroque-style buildings in Budapest and one of the finest examples of preserved Baroque-style architecture is the Church of St.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] An interesting part of Budapest is the less touristy Óbuda, the main square of which also has some beautiful preserved historic buildings with Baroque façades.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Castle District is another place to visit where the best-known landmark Buda Royal Palace and many other buildings were built in the Baroque style.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Classical architecture and Neoclassical architecture are the next in the timeline.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest had not one but two architects that were masters of the Classicist style.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Mihály Pollack (1773–1855) and József Hild (1789–1867), built many beautiful Classicist-style buildings in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some of the best examples are the Hungarian National Museum, the Lutheran Church of Budavár (both designed by Pollack) and the seat of the Hungarian president, the Sándor Palace.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The most iconic and widely known Classicist-style attraction in Budapest is the Széchenyi Chain Bridge.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest's two most beautiful Romantic architecture buildings are the Great Synagogue in Dohány Street and the Vigadó Concert Hall on the Danube Promenade, both designed by architect Frigyes Feszl (1821–1884).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Another noteworthy structure is the Budapest Western Railway Station, which was designed by August de Serres and built by the Eiffel Company of Paris in 1877.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Art Nouveau came into fashion in Budapest by the exhibitions which were held in and around 1896 and organised in connection with the Hungarian Millennium celebrations.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Art Nouveau in Hungary (*Szecesszió* in Hungarian) is a blend of several architectural styles, with a focus on Hungary's specialities.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] One of the leading Art Nouveau architects, Ödön Lechner (1845–1914), was inspired by Indian and Syrian architecture as well as traditional Hungarian decorative designs.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] One of his most beautiful buildings in Budapest is the Museum of Applied Arts.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Another examples for Art Nouveau in Budapest is the Gresham Palace in front of the Chain Bridge, the Hotel Gellért, the Franz Liszt Academy of Music or Budapest Zoo and Botanical Garden.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The second half of the 20th century also saw, under the communist regime, the construction of blocks of flats (panelház), as in other Eastern European countries.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In the 21st century, Budapest faces new challenges in its architecture.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The pressure towards the high-rise buildings is unequivocal among today's world cities, but preserving Budapest's unique cityscape and its very diverse architecture, along with green areas, forces Budapest to balance between them.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The Contemporary architecture has wide margin in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Public spaces attract heavy investment by business and government also, so that the city has gained entirely new (or renovated and redesigned) squares, parks and monuments, for example the city central Kossuth Lajos square, Deák Ferenc square and Liberty Square.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Numerous landmarks have been created in the last decade in Budapest, like the National Theatre, Palace of Arts, Rákóczi Bridge, Megyeri Bridge, Budapest Airport Sky Court among others, and millions of square meters of new office buildings and apartments.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] But there are still large opportunities in real estate development in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Contemporary Budapest is divided into 23 districts (Hungarian: *kerületek*, sing.: *kerület*), each with a mayor and municipal government elected separately from the general municipal government.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The districts and the general municipal government have constitutionally and legally defined, non-overlapping areas of competence.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Each district has a municipally recognized name, some of which correspond to how locals call that area or neighborhood (e.g., Belváros, V. district; Terézváros, VI. district), others which (e.g., Újbuda, XI. district) are neologisms.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Street signs display the district and that neighborhood's colloquial name.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The latter are often the names of villages that were gradually annexed to the city (e.g., Sashalom, Budafok) or of superseded administrative units of former boroughs.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] After the unification of Buda, Pest, and Óbuda in 1873, Budapest initially had 10 districts.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] It was during the interwar period that Károly Szendy's 1934-1944 mayoral administration first seriously considered annexing peripheral towns and villages.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This only came about, however, after the rise of state communism in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 1950, for reasons of social and industrial policy—including the Hungarian Working People's Party's desire to proletarianize the traditionally right-wing suburbs—7 cities with county rights and 16 towns were annexed to the capital to form contemporary Greater Budapest (Hungarian: *Nagy-Budapest*).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This reorganized the city into 22 districts, a number that grew to 23 after Soroksár seceded from Pesterzsébet in 1994.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The contemporary city thus consists of 6 districts in Buda, 16 in Pest, and Csepel.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Today, districts I., II., XI., and XII. in Buda and V., VI., VII., VIII., and IX. in Pest make up the city centre in its broadest sense, corresponding roughly to the 1873 municipal boundaries.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest's districts are numbered according to three concentric semicircles.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The I. district is a small area in central Buda, including the Castle Quarter.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] District II. is in Buda to the castle's northwest while district III. stretches along the northernmost part of Buda and includes the former Óbuda.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] District IV. continues this semicircle in northernmost Pest, but the V. district is in the very centre of Pest and inaugurates a new circle that then loops back through Pest to Buda as the VI., VII., VIII., IX., XI., and XII. districts.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Districts XIII., XIV., XV., XVI., XVII., XVIII., XIX., XX., XXI., and XXII. form yet another semicircle in outermost Pest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Districts X. and XXIII. form irregularities within the overall pattern.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is the most populous city in Hungary and one of the largest cities in the European Union, with a growing number of inhabitants, estimated at 1,763,913 in 2019, whereby inward migration exceeds outward migration.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] These trends are also seen throughout the Budapest metropolitan area, which is home to 3.3 million people.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This amounts to about 34% of Hungary's population.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In 2014, the city had a population density of 3,314 people/km2 (8,580 people/mi2), rendering it the most densely populated of all municipalities in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The population density of Elisabethtown-District VII is 30,989/km2 (80,260/mi2), which has the highest population density figure in Hungary and one of the highest in the world.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] For comparison, the density in Manhattan is 25,846/km2.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is the fourth most "dynamically growing city" by population in Europe, and the Euromonitor predicts a population increase of almost 10% between 2005 and 2030.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The European Observation Network for Territorial Development and Cohesion says Budapest's population will increase by 10% to 30% only due to migration by 2050.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] A constant inflow of migrants in recent years has fuelled population growth in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Productivity gains and the relatively large economically active share of the population explain why household incomes have increased in Budapest to a greater extent than in other parts of Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Higher incomes in Budapest are reflected in the lower share of expenditure the city's inhabitants allocate to necessary spending such as on food and non-alcoholic drinks.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] According to the 2016 microcensus, there were 1,764,263 people living in Budapest in 907,944 dwellings.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Some 1.6 million persons from the metropolitan area may be within Budapest's boundaries during working hours, and during special events.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] This fluctuation in the population is caused by hundreds of thousands of suburban residents who travel to the city for work, education, health care, and special events.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] In Hungary people can declare multiple ethnic identities, hence the sum may exceed 100%.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The share of ethnic Hungarians in Budapest (96.2%) is slightly lower than the national average (98.3%) due to the international migration.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] According to the 2011 census, 1,712,153 people (99.0%) speak Hungarian, of whom 1,692,815 people (97.9%) speak it as a first language, while 19,338 people (1.1%) speak it as a second language.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] According to the same census, 1,600,585 people (92.6%) were born in Hungary, 126,036 people (7.3%) outside Hungary while the birthplace of 2,419 people (0.1%) was unknown.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Although only 1.7% of the population of Hungary in 2009 were foreigners, 43% of them lived in Budapest, making them 4.4% of the city's population (up from 2% in 2001).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Nearly two-thirds of foreigners living in Hungary were under 40 years old.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The primary motivation for this age group living in Hungary was employment.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] Budapest is home to one of the most populous Christian communities in Central Europe, numbering 698,521 people (40.4%) in 2011.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p01] The city is home to the fifth largest Jewish community in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] On a national level, Budapest is the primate city of Hungary regarding business and the economy, accounting for 39% of the national income.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city had a gross metropolitan product of more than $100 billion in 2015, making it one of the largest regional economies in the European Union.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] According to Eurostat GDP, per capita in purchasing power parity is 147% of the EU average in Budapest, which means €37,632 ($42,770) per capita.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is also among the Top 100 GDP performing cities in the world, measured by PricewaterhouseCoopers.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city was named as the 52nd most important business centre in the world in the Worldwide Centres of Commerce Index, ahead of Beijing, São Paulo and Shenzhen and ranking 3rd (out of 65 cities) on the MasterCard Emerging Markets Index.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is 48th on the UBS *The most expensive and richest cities in the world* list, standing before cities such as Prague, Shanghai, Kuala Lumpur and Buenos Aires.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In a global city competitiveness ranking by the EIU, Budapest stands before Tel Aviv, Lisbon, Moscow and Johannesburg among others.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is a major centre for banking and finance, real estate, retailing, trade, transportation, tourism, new media as well as traditional media, advertising, legal services, accountancy, insurance, fashion and the arts in Hungary and regionally.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is home not only to almost all national institutions and government agencies, but also to many domestic and international companies.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In 2014 there were 395.804 companies registered in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Most of these entities are headquartered in Budapest's Central Business District, in District V and District XIII.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The retail market of the city (and the country) is also concentrated in the downtown area, among others, in the two largest shopping centres in Central and Eastern Europe, the 186,000 sqm WestEnd City Center and the 180,000 sqm Arena Plaza.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has notable innovation capabilities as a technology and start-up hub.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Many start-ups are headquartered and begin their business in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Some of the best known examples are Prezi, LogMeIn and NNG.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is the highest ranked Central and Eastern European city in the Innovation Cities' Top 100 index.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Moreover, the global aspect of the city's research activity is shown through the establishment of the European Chinese Research Institute in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Other important sectors also include, natural science research, information technology and medical research, non-profit institutions, and universities.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The leading business schools and universities in Budapest, the Budapest Business School, the CEU Business School and Corvinus University of Budapest offer a whole range of courses in economics, finance and management in English, French, German and Hungarian.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The unemployment rate in Budapest is by far the lowest within Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] It was 2.7%, with many thousands of employed foreign citizens.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is among the 25 most visited cities in the world, welcoming more than 4.4 million international visitors each year, therefore the traditional and the congress tourism industry also deserve a mention, as they contribute greatly to the city's economy.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The capital is home to many convention centres and there are thousands of restaurants, bars, coffee houses and party places, besides a full range of hotels.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As regards restaurants, examples can be found of the highest quality Michelin-starred restaurants, such as Onyx, Costes, Tanti and Borkonyha.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city ranked as the most liveable city in Central and Eastern Europe on EIU's quality of life index in 2010.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Stock Exchange, a key institution of publicly offered securities in Hungary and Central and Eastern Europe, is situated in Budapest's CBD at Liberty Square.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] BSE also trades other securities such as government bonds and derivatives as well as stock options.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Large Hungarian multinational corporations headquartered in Budapest are listed on the BSE, for instance the Fortune Global 500 firms MOL Group, the OTP Bank, FHB Bank, Gedeon Richter, Magyar Telekom, CIG Pannonia, Zwack Unicum and more.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Nowadays nearly all branches of industry can be found in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Although there is no particularly special industry in the city's economy, the financial centre role of the city is strong, with nearly 40 major banks being represented in the city including as well as those like Bank of China, KDB Bank and Hanwha Bank, which are unique in the region.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Many international banks and financial service providers also support the financial industry of Budapest, firms such as Citigroup, Morgan Stanley, GE Capital, Deutsche Bank, Sberbank, ING Group, Allianz, KBC Group, UniCredit, Wise (company) and MSCI among others.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Another particularly strong industry in the capital city is the biotechnology and pharmaceutical industry.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are also traditionally strong domestic companies in Budapest such as Egis, Gedeon Richter, Chinoin as well as international biotechnology corporations such as Pfizer, Teva, Novartis, Sanofi, which also have R&D and production divisions here.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Further high-tech industries, involved in software development and engineering are notable as well.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Nokia, Ericsson, Bosch, Microsoft and IBM employ thousands of engineers in research and development in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Game design is also strongly represented with headquarters of domestic companies Digital Reality, Black Hole and the studios of Crytek and Gameloft.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Apart from the above, there are regional headquarters of global firms such as Alcoa, General Motors, General Electric, ExxonMobil, BP, BT, Flextronics, Panasonic, Huawei, Knorr-Bremse, Liberty Global, Tata Consultancy, Aegon, WizzAir, TriGránit, MVM Group and Graphisoft.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There is a base for major international companies including, but not limited to, Nissan CEE, Volvo, Saab and Ford.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As the capital of Hungary, Budapest is the seat of the country's national government.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The President of Hungary resides at the Sándor Palace in the District I (Buda Castle District), while the office of the Hungarian Prime Minister is in the Carmelite Monastery in the Castle District.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Government ministries are all located in various parts of the city, most of them are in the District V, Leopoldtown.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The National Assembly is seated in the Hungarian Parliament, which also located in the District V.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The President of the National Assembly, the third-highest public official in Hungary, is also seated in the largest building in the country, in the Hungarian Parliament.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungary's highest courts are located in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Curia (supreme court of Hungary), the highest court in the judicial order, which reviews criminal and civil cases, is located in the District V, Leopoldtown.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Under the authority of its president it has three departments: criminal, civil and administrative-labour law departments.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Curia guarantees the uniform application of law.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The decisions of the Curia on uniform jurisdiction are binding for other courts.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Constitutional Court of Hungary is one of the highest level actors independent of the politics in the country.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Constitutional Court serves as the main body for the protection of the Constitution, its tasks being the review of the constitutionality of statutes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Constitutional Court performs its tasks independently.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] With its own budget and its judges being elected by Parliament it does not constitute a part of the ordinary judicial system.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The constitutional court passes on the constitutionality of laws, and there is no right of appeal on these decisions.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is also home to more than 100 embassies and representative bodies as an international political actor.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Environmental issues have a high priority among Budapest's politics.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Institutions such as the Regional Environmental Center for Central and Eastern Europe, located in Budapest, are very important assets.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] To decrease the use of cars and greenhouse gas emissions, the city has worked to improve public transportation, and nowadays the city has one of the highest mass transit usage in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has one of the best public transport systems in Europe with an efficient network of buses, trolleys, trams and subway.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has an above-average proportion of people commuting on public transport or walking and cycling for European cities.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Riding on bike paths is one of the best ways to see Budapest – there are about 180 kilometres (110 miles) of bicycle paths in the city, fitting into the EuroVelo system.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Crime in Budapest is investigated by different bodies.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime notes in their 2011 Global Study on Homicide that, according to criminal justice sources, the homicide rate in Hungary, calculated based on UN population estimates, was 1.4 in 2009, compared to Canada's rate of 1.8 that same year.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The homicide rate in Budapest is below the EU capital cities' average according to WHO also.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] However, organised crime is associated with the city, the Institute of Defence in a UN study named Budapest as one of the "global epicentres" of illegal pornography, money laundering and contraband tobacco, and also a negotiation centre for international crime group leaders.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has been a metropolitan municipality with a mayor-council form of government since its consolidation in 1873, but Budapest also holds a special status as a county-level government, and also special within that, as holds a capital-city territory status.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In Budapest, the central government is responsible for the urban planning, statutory planning, public transport, housing, waste management, municipal taxes, correctional institutions, libraries, public safety, recreational facilities, among others.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Mayor is responsible for all city services, police and fire protection, enforcement of all city and state laws within the city, and administration of public property and most public agencies.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Besides, each of Budapest' twenty-three districts has its own town hall and a directly elected council and the directly elected mayor of district.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Mayor of Budapest is Gergely Karácsony who was elected on 13 October 2019.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The mayor and members of General Assembly are elected to five-year terms.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest General Assembly is a unicameral body consisting of 33 members, which consist of the 23 mayors of the districts, 9 from the electoral lists of political parties, plus Mayor of Budapest (the Mayor is elected directly).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Each term for the mayor and assembly members lasts five years.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Submitting the budget of Budapest is the responsibility of the Mayor and the deputy-mayor in charge of finance.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The latest, 2014 budget was approved with 18 supporting votes from ruling Fidesz and 14 votes against by the opposition lawmakers.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is widely known for its well-kept pre-war cityscape, with a great variety of streets and landmarks in classical architecture.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The most well-known sight of the capital is the neo-Gothic Parliament, the biggest building in Hungary with its 268 metres (879 ft) length, also holding (since 2001) the Hungarian Crown Jewels.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Saint Stephen's Basilica is the most important religious building of the city, where the Holy Right Hand of Hungary's first king, Saint Stephen is on display as well.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungarian cuisine and café culture can be seen and tasted in many places, like Gerbeaud Café, the *Százéves*, *Biarritz*, *Fortuna*, *Alabárdos*, *Arany Szarvas*, *Gundel* and the world-famous Mátyás-pince restaurants and beer bars.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are Roman remains at the Aquincum Museum, and historic furniture at the Nagytétény Castle Museum, just 2 of 223 museums in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Another historical museum is the House of Terror, hosted in the building that was the venue of the Nazi Headquarters.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Castle Hill, the River Danube embankments and the whole of Andrássy út have been officially recognized as UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Castle Hill and the Castle District; there are three churches here, six museums, and a host of interesting buildings, streets and squares.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The former Royal Palace is one of the symbols of Hungary – and has been the scene of battles and wars ever since the 13th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Nowadays it houses two museums and the National Széchenyi Library.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The nearby Sándor Palace contains the offices and official residence of the President of Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The seven-hundred-year-old Matthias Church is one of the jewels of Budapest, it is in neo-Gothic style, decorated with coloured shingles and elegant pinnacles.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Statues of the Turul, the mythical guardian bird of Hungary, can be found in both the Castle District and the Twelfth District.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In Pest, arguably the most important sight is Andrássy út.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] This Avenue is an elegant 2.5 kilometres (2 miles) long tree-lined street that covers the distance from Deák Ferenc tér to the Heroes Square.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] This Avenue overlooks many important sites.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As far as Kodály körönd and Oktogon both sides are lined with large shops and flats built close together.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Between there and Heroes' Square the houses are detached and altogether grander.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Under the whole runs continental Europe's oldest Underground railway, most of whose stations retain their original appearance.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Heroes' Square is dominated by the Millenary Monument, with the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in front.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] To the sides are the Museum of Fine Arts and the Kunsthalle Budapest, and behind City Park opens out, with Vajdahunyad Castle.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] One of the jewels of Andrássy út is the Hungarian State Opera House.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Statue Park, a theme park with striking statues of the Communist era, is located just outside the main city and is accessible by public transport.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Dohány Street Synagogue is the largest synagogue in Europe, and the second largest active synagogue in the world.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The synagogue is located in the Jewish district taking up several blocks in central Budapest bordered by Király utca, Wesselényi utca, Grand Boulevard and Bajcsy Zsilinszky road.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] It was built in moorish revival style in 1859 and has a seating capacity of 3,000.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Adjacent to it is a sculpture reproducing a weeping willow tree in steel to commemorate the Hungarian victims of the Holocaust.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is also home to the largest medicinal bath in Europe (Széchenyi Medicinal Bath) and the third largest Parliament building in the world, once the largest in the world.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Other attractions are the bridges of the capital.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Most remarkable for their beauty are the Margaret Bridge, the Chain Bridge and the Liberty Bridge.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The world's largest panorama photograph was created in (and of) Budapest in 2010.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Tourists visiting Budapest can receive free maps and information from the nonprofit Budapest Festival and Tourism Center at its info-points.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The info centres also offer the Budapest Card which allows free public transit and discounts for several museums, restaurants and other places of interest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Cards are available for 24-, 48- or 72-hour durations.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is also well known for its ruin bars both day and night.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has many municipal parks and most have playgrounds for children and seasonal activities like skating in the winter and boating in the summer.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Access from the city centre is quick and easy with the Millennium Underground.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest has a complex park system, with various lands operated by the Budapest City Gardening Ltd.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The most notable and popular parks in Budapest are the City Park which was established in 1751 (302 acres) along with Andrássy Avenue, the Margaret Island in the Danube (238 acres or 96 hectares), the People's Park, the Római Part, and the Kopaszi Dam.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Buda Hills also offer a variety of outdoor activities and views.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] A place frequented by locals is Normafa, offering activities for all seasons.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] With a modest ski run, it is also used by skiers and snowboarders – if there is enough snowfall in winter.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The islands of Palotai Island, Nép Island, and Háros Island also formerly existed within the city, but have been joined to the mainland.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Ínség Rock (Hungarian: *Ínség-szikla*) is a reef in the Danube close to the shore under the Gellért Hill.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] It is only exposed during drought periods when the river level is very low.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Just outside the city boundary to the north lies the large Szentendre Island (Hungarian: *Szentendrei-sziget*) and the much smaller Lupa Island (Hungarian: *Lupa-sziget*).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] One of the reasons the Romans first colonised the area immediately to the west of the River Danube and established their regional capital at Aquincum (now part of Óbuda, in northern Budapest) is so that they could use and enjoy the thermal springs.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are still ruins visible today of the enormous baths that were built during that period.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The new baths that were constructed during the Turkish period (1541–1686) served both bathing and medicinal purposes, and some of these are still in use to this day.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest gained its reputation as a city of spas in the 1920s, following the first realisation of the economic potential of the thermal waters in drawing in visitors.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Indeed, in 1934 Budapest was officially ranked as a "City of Spas".
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Today, the baths are mostly frequented by the older generation, as, with the exception of the "Magic Bath" and "Cinetrip" water discos, young people tend to prefer the lidos which are open in the summer.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Construction of the Király Baths started in 1565, and most of the present-day building dates from the Turkish period, including most notably the fine cupola-topped pool.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Rudas Baths are centrally placed – in the narrow strip of land between Gellért Hill and the River Danube – and also an outstanding example of architecture dating from the Turkish period.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The central feature is an octagonal pool over which light shines from a 10 metres (33 ft) diameter cupola, supported by eight pillars.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Gellért Baths and Hotel were built in 1918, although there had once been Turkish baths on the site, and in the Middle Ages a hospital.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In 1927, the Baths were extended to include the wave pool, and the effervescent bath was added in 1934.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The well-preserved Art Nouveau interior includes colourful mosaics, marble columns, stained glass windows and statues.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Lukács Baths are also in Buda and are also Turkish in origin, although they were only revived at the end of the 19th century.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] This was also when the spa and treatment centre were founded.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There is still something of an atmosphere of fin-de-siècle about the place, and all around the inner courtyard there are marble tablets recalling the thanks of patrons who were cured there.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Since the 1950s it has been regarded as a centre for intellectuals and artists.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Széchenyi Baths are one of the largest bathing complexes in all Europe, and the only "old" medicinal baths to be found in the Pest side of the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The indoor medicinal baths date from 1913 and the outdoor pools from 1927.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There is an atmosphere of grandeur about the whole place with the bright, largest pools resembling aspects associated with Roman baths, the smaller bath tubs reminding one of the bathing culture of the Greeks, and the saunas and diving pools borrowed from traditions emanating in northern Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The three outdoor pools (one of which is a fun pool) are open all year, including winter.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Indoors there are over ten separate pools, and a whole host of medical treatments is also available.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Szécheny Baths are built in modern Renaissance style.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is served by Budapest Ferenc Liszt International Airport (BUD) (named after Franz Liszt, the notable Hungarian composer), one of the busiest airports in Central and Eastern Europe, located 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) east-southeast of the centre of Budapest, in the District XVIII.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The airport offers international connections among all major European cities, and also to North America, Africa, Asia and the Middle East.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As Hungary's busiest airport, it handles nearly all of the country's air passenger traffic.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest Liszt Ferenc handled around 250 scheduled flights daily in 2013, and an ever-rising number of charters.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] London, Brussels, Frankfurt, Munich, Paris, and Amsterdam are the busiest international connections respectively, while Toronto, Montreal, Dubai, Doha and Alicante are the most unusual in the region.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Today the airport serves as a base for Ryanair, Wizz Air, Budapest Aircraft Service, LOT Polish Airlines and Smartwings Hungary among others.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The airport is accessible via public transportation from the city centre by the Metro line 3 and then the airport bus 200E and 100E.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As part of a strategic development plan, €561 million have been spent on expanding and modernising the airport infrastructure until December 2012.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Most of these improvements are already completed, the postponed ones are the new cargo area and new piers for terminal 2A and 2B, but these development are on standby also, and will start immediately, when the airport traffic will reach the appropriate level.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] SkyCourt, the newest, state-of-the-art building between the 2A and 2B terminals with 5 levels.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Passenger safety checks were moved here along with new baggage classifiers and the new Malév and SkyTeam business lounges, as well as the first MasterCard lounge in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Public transit in Budapest is provided by the Centre for Budapest Transport (BKK, *Budapesti Közlekedési Központ*), one of the largest transportation authorities in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] BKK operates 4 metro lines (including the historic Line 1, the oldest underground railway in continental Europe), 5 suburban railway lines, 33 tram lines, 15 trolleybus lines, 264 bus lines (including 40 night routes), 4 boat services, and *BuBi*, a smart bicycle sharing network.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] On an average weekday, BKK lines transports 3.9 million riders; in 2011, it handled a total of 1.4 billion passengers.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In 2014, the 65% of the passenger traffic in Budapest was by public transport and 35% by car.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The aim is 80%–20% by 2030 in accordance with the strategy of BKK.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] People aged 65 and over and under 14 travel free.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Public transport users are immediately notified of any changes in public transport online, on smartphones and on PIDS displays, as well car drivers can keep track of changes in traffic and road management in real-time online and on smartphones through the *BKK Info*.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] As well all vehicles can be followed online and on smartphones in real-time throughout the city with the *Futár* PIDS system, while the continuous introducing of integrated e-ticket system will help the measurement of passenger numbers on each line and the intelligent control of service frequency.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The development of *Futár*, the citywide real-time passenger information system and real-time route planner is finished already and now all of the public transport vehicle is connected via satellite system.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The real-time information of trams, buses and trolleybuses are available for both the operators in the control room and for all the passengers in all stops on smartphone and on city street displays.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The deployment of 300 new digital contactless ticket vending machine will be finished by the end of 2014 in harmonization with the e-ticket system.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] 4 and 6 are the busiest city tram lines in the world, with one of the world's longest trams (54-metre long Siemens Combino) running at 2–3-minute intervals at peak time and 4–5 minutes off-peak.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Day services are usually from 4 am until between 11 pm and 0:30 am.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungarian State Railways operates an extensive network of commuter rail services, their importance in the suburban commuter passenger traffic is significant, but in travel within the city is limited.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is the most important Hungarian road terminus, all of the major highways and railways end within the city limits.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The road system in the city is designed in a similar manner to that of Paris, with several ring roads, and avenues radiating out from the centre.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Ring road M0 around Budapest is nearly completed, with only one section missing on the west side due to local disputes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The ring road is 80 kilometres (50 miles) in length, and once finished it will be 107 kilometres (66 mi) of highway in length.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is a vital traffic hub because all major European roads and European railway lines lead to Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Danube was and is still today an important water-way and this region in the centre of the Carpathian Basin lies at the cross-roads of trade routes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungarian main line railways are operated by Hungarian State Railways.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are three main railway stations in Budapest, Keleti (*Eastern*), Nyugati (*Western*) and Déli (*Southern*), operating both domestic and international rail services.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is one of the main stops of the Orient Express on its Central and Eastern European route.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There is also a suburban rail service in and around Budapest, three lines of which are operated under the name HÉV.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The river Danube flows through Budapest on its way from (Germany) to the Black Sea.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The river is easily navigable and so Budapest historically has a major commercial port at Csepel District and at New Pest District also.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Pest side is also a famous port place with international shipping ports for cargo and for passenger ships.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In the summer months, a scheduled hydrofoil service operates on the Danube connecting the city to Vienna.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] BKK (through the operator BKV) also provides public transport with boat service within the borders of the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Two routes, marked D11 and D12, connect the two banks with Margaret Island and Óbuda Island, from Rómaifürdő (Buda side, north to Óbuda Island) or Árpád Bridge (Pest side) to Rákóczi Bridge, with a total of 18 stops, while route D2 circulates in the downtown.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Line D14 is a ferry service, connecting Királyerdő on the Csepel Island with Molnár Island on the Pest side, south to the city centre.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In addition, several companies provides sightseeing boat trips and also an amphibious vehicle (bus and boat) operates constantly.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Water quality in Budapest harbours improved dramatically in the recent years, treatment facilities processed 100% of generated sewage in 2010.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapesters regularly kayak, canoe, jet-ski and sail on the Danube, which has continuously become a major recreational site for the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Special vehicles in Budapest, besides metros, include suburban rails, trams and boats.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are a couple of less common vehicles in Budapest, like the trolleybus on several lines in Pest, the Castle Hill Funicular between the Chain Bridge and Buda Castle, the cyclecar for rent in Margaret Island, the chairlift, the Budapest Cog-wheel Railway and children's railway.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The latter three vehicles run among Buda hills.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The culture of Budapest is reflected by Budapest's size and variety.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Most Hungarian cultural movements first emerged in the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is an important centre for music, film, theatre, dance and visual art.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Artists have been drawn into the city by opportunity, as the city government funds the arts with adequate financial resources.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest was named "City of Design" in December 2015 and has been a member of UNESCO Creative Cities Network since then.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is packed with museums and galleries.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city glories in 223 museums and galleries, which presents several memories, next to the Hungarian ones as well those of universal and European culture and science.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In Budapest there are 837 monuments, which represent most of the European artistic styles.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The classical and unique Hungarian Art Nouveau buildings are prominent.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Many libraries have unique collections in Budapest, such as the National Széchényi Library, which keeps historical relics from the age before the printing of books.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Metropolitan Szabó Ervin Library plays an important role in the general education of the capital's population.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Other libraries: The Library of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences, Eötvös University Library, the Parliamentary Library, Library of the Hungarian Central Statistical Office and the National Library of Foreign Literature.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In Budapest there are forty theatres, seven concert halls and an opera house.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Outdoor festivals, concerts and lectures enrich the cultural offer of summer, which are often held in historical buildings.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Opera Ball is an annual Hungarian society event taking place in the building of the Budapest Opera (*Operaház*) on the last Saturday of the carnival season, usually late February.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are 11 casinos in Hungary (11 is the maximum number of casinos allowed by law), and five of them are located in the capital.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] All five of these casinos were owned by LVC Diamond Játékkaszinó Üzemeltető Kft, the gambling company of late András Vajna (better known as Andy Vajna) until his death in 2017.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The biggest casino in Budapest and in all of Hungary is the Las Vegas Casino at the Corvin promenade.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Several annual festivals take place in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Sziget Festival is one of the largest outdoor music festivals in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Spring Festival includes concerts at several venues across the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Café Budapest Contemporary Arts Festival (formerly the Budapest Autumn Festival) brings free music, dance, art, and other cultural events to the streets of the city.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Wine Festival and Budapest Pálinka Festival, occurring each May, are gastronomy festivals focusing on culinary pleasures.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Pride (or Budapest Pride Film and Cultural Festival) occurs annually across the city, and usually involves a parade on the Andrássy Avenue.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Other festivals include the Budapest Fringe Festival, which brings more than 500 artists in about 50 shows to produce a wide range of works in alternative theatre, dance, music and comedy outside the mainstream.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The LOW Festival is a contemporary cultural festival held in Hungary in the cities Budapest and Pécs from February until March; the name of the festival alludes to the Low Countries, the region encompassing the Netherlands and Flanders.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The Budapest Jewish Summer Festival, in late August, is one of the largest in Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] There are many symphony orchestras in Budapest, with the Budapest Philharmonic Orchestra being the preeminent one.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] It was founded in 1853 by Ferenc Erkel and still presents regular concerts in the Hungarian State Opera House and National Theatre.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest also has one of the more active jazz scenes in Central Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The dance tradition of the Carpathian Basin is a unique area of the European dance culture, which is also a special transition between the Balkans and Western Europe regions.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The city is home to several authentic Hungarian folk dance ensembles which range from small ensembles to professional troupes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is one of the few cities in the world with a high school for learning folk dance.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is home to a fashion week twice a year, where the city's fashion designers and houses present their collections and provide a meeting place for the fashion industry representatives.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest Fashion Week additionally a place for designers from other countries may present their collections in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungarian models, like Barbara Palvin, Enikő Mihalik, Diána Mészáros, Viktória Vámosi usually appear at these events along international participants.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Fashion brands like Zara, H&M, Mango, ESPRIT, Douglas AG, Lacoste, Tommy Hilfiger, Guess, Nike and other retail fashion brands are common across the city's shopping malls and on the streets.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is a prominent location for the Hungarian entertainment industry, with many films, television series, books, and other media set there.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest is the largest centre for film and television production in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In 2011, it employed more than 50,000 people and generated 63.9% of revenues of the media industry in the country.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Documentary channels include Discovery Channel, Discovery Science, Discovery World, National Geographic Channel, Nat Geo Wild, Spektrum TV, and BBC Entertainment.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] This is less than a quarter of the channels broadcast from Budapest; for the whole picture see Television in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In 2012, in Hungary there were 7.2 million internet users (72% of the population) and 2.3 million subscriptions for mobile broadband.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] In the modern age, Budapest developed its own peculiar cuisine, based on products of the nearby region, such as lamb, pork and vegetables special to the region.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Modern Hungarian cuisine is a synthesis of ancient Asiatic components mixed with French, Germanic, Italian, and Slavic elements.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] The food of Hungary can be considered a melting pot of the continent, with a culinary base formed from its own, original Magyar cuisine.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Considerable numbers of Saxons, Armenians, Italians, Jews and Serbs settled in the Hungarian basin and in Transylvania, also contributing with different new dishes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Hungarian cuisine was influenced by Austrian cuisine under the Austro-Hungarian Empire, dishes and methods of food preparation have often been borrowed from Austrian cuisine, and vice versa.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest restaurants reflect diversity, with menus carrying traditional regional cuisine, fusions of various culinary influences, or innovating in the leading edge of new techniques.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] Budapest's food shops also have a solid reputation for supplying quality specialised culinary products and supplies, reputations that are often built up over generations.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] These include many shop and served in several Michelin-starred restaurants.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] *The Grand Budapest Hotel* (2014) is a Wes Anderson film.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p02] It was filmed in Germany, and set in the fictional Republic of Zubrowka, which is in the alpine mountains of Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] In 2015, the Assembly of the Hungarian Olympic Committee and the Assembly of Budapest decided to bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Budapest has lost several bids to host the games, in 1916, 1920, 1936, 1944, and 1960 to Berlin, Antwerp, London, and Rome, respectively.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The Hungarian Parliament also voted to support the bid on 28 January 2016, later Budapest City Council approved list of venues and Budapest became an official candidate for the 2024 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] However, they withdrew their bid later on.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Numerous Olympic, World, and European Championship winners and medalists reside in the city, which follows from Hungary's 8th place among all the nations of the world in the All-time Olympic Games medal table.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Hungarians have always been avid sports people: during the history of the Summer Olympic Games, Hungarians have brought home 476 medals, of which 167 are gold.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The top events in which Hungarians have excelled are fencing, swimming, water polo, canoeing, wrestling and track & field sports.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Beside classic sports, recreational modern sports such as bowling, pool billiard, darts, go-carting, wakeboarding and squash are very popular in Budapest, and extreme sports are also gaining ground.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Furthermore, the Budapest Marathon and Budapest Half Marathon also attract many people every year.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The city's largest football stadium is named after Ferenc Puskás, recognised as the top scorer of the 20th century and for whom FIFA Puskás Award was named.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The Hungarian Grand Prix in Formula One has been held at the Hungaroring just outside the city, a circuit which has FIA Grade 1 license.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Since 1986, the race has been a round of the FIA Formula One World Championship.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] At the 2013 Hungarian Grand Prix, it was confirmed that Hungary will continue to host a Formula 1 race until 2021.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The track was completely resurfaced for the first time in early 2016, and it was announced the Grand Prix's deal was extended for a further five years, until 2026.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Budapest is home to two four-star UEFA stadiums: Puskás Aréna, Groupama Aréna, and two three-star UEFA stadiums: Hidegkuti Nándor Stadion and Bozsik Aréna (currently under renovations to upgrade to UEFA's four-star category).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Budapest will be the home of the headquarters of the World Aquatics after moving from Lausanne by the 2027 World Aquatics Championships.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Budapest is home to over 35 higher education institutions, many of which are universities.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Under the Bologna Process, many offered qualifications are recognised in countries across Europe.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Medicine, dentistry, pharmaceuticals, veterinary programs, and engineering are among the most popular fields for foreigners to undertake in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Most universities in Budapest offer courses in English, as well as in other languages like German, French, and Dutch, aimed specifically at foreigners.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Many students from other European countries spend one or two semesters in Budapest through the Erasmus Programme.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Budapest has quite a few sister cities and many partner cities around the world.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Like Budapest, many of them are the most influential and largest cities of their country and region, most of them are the primate city and political, economical, cultural capital of their country.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] The Mayor of Budapest says the aim of improving sister city relationships is to allow and encourage a mutual exchange of information and experiences, as well as co-operation, in the areas of city management, education, culture, tourism, media and communication, trade and business development.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-p03] Some of the city's districts are also twinned to small cities or districts of other big cities; for details see the article List of districts in Budapest.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The **Budapest University of Technology and Economics** (Hungarian: *Budapesti Műszaki és Gazdaságtudományi Egyetem*, shortened to *Műegyetem*), official abbreviation **BME**, is a public research university located in Budapest, Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] It is the most significant university of technology in the country and is considered the world's oldest institute of technology with university rank and structure, founded in 1782.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] More than 110 departments and institutes operate within eight faculties.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The University employs about 1100 lecturers, 400 researchers and other degree holders as well as numerous invited lecturers and practising specialists, including 34 members of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Approximately 1381 of the university's 21,171 students are foreigners, coming from 50 countries.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The University issues about 70% of Hungary's engineering degrees.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Training courses are provided in five languages: Hungarian, English, German, French and Russian.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The ECTS credit system was introduced in 1995.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] This helps students to enroll in the student exchange program of the European Union, the Socrates (or Erasmus) program, and earn a double degree through the Top Industrial Managers for Europe network.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Budapest University of Technology and Economics (BME) is a public higher education institute operating as a central budgetary institution.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Its founding regulation has been issued by the Minister of Human Resources.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Its Organizational and operational conditions are summarized in its own regulation in accordance with laws.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The steering body of the university is the Senate.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Education, research, innovation and direct additional services are proceeded by the faculties.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Work-sharing between the faculties are subject oriented both in the fields of education and that of technology.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The organogram of BME is available here.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The faculties consist of departments, institutes, research centres that are supported by deans offices and other units.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Governing is assisted by the Rectors Office and the Chancellors Office.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] There is a highly independent Group of integrated internal control.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Faculties and Students organizations are supported by service units.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] There are other organizations like companies established or owned by the university, welfare institutions, student or teacher activity groups and other organizations associated to the university.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Rector is the top manager and representative of the university.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Chancellor ensures the technical conditions, the administration, the financial management in order to complete the functions of the university.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Rector and the Chancellor regularly calls executive board meetings to prepare strategic decisions.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Employment relations between are regulated in the Annex of the Human Resource Policy.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] All Hungarians who pass the Hungarian secondary school matura with enough points are eligible for admission, as well as for anyone else in possession of an International Baccalaureate (again, with enough points).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] As with all Hungarian universities, a tuition fee of around $1000 has to be paid each semester for the Hungarian program.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] No extra fee is required for Hungarians for whom it is their first university, unless they spend more than 13 semesters there.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The university offers extensive English language programs on all its faculties, at all levels of study (Preparatory Year, Bachelor of Science, Bachelor of Arts, Master of Science, Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Tuition fees vary from €2000 - €4500 per semester.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] 6% of all students come from over fifty countries; the majority of the students in the English Program are from Azerbaijan, China, Pakistan, Kazakhstan and Jordan in the greatest numbers, and students from Malaysia, Ecuador and Saudi-Arabia are among the graduates.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The university is located on the Buda side of the Danube between Szabadság Bridge and Petőfi Bridge and towards Rákóczi Bridge.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] This makes the university campus especially long and narrow: walking from one side of the university to the other can take as much as 20 minutes.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Inner City of Budapest (Pest) is just across the river, about 10 minutes' walk by either of the bridges.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The university has one sports club, the Műegyetemi AFC, which played in the first 1901 Hungarian League season.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The university hosted the IFIUS 2008 World Interuniversity Games in October.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The National Technical Information Centre and Library at the Budapest University of Technology and Economics (BME OMIKK) is the successor of two major libraries in Hungary.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The library of the Budapest University of Technology and Economics (then Joseph Polytechnics) was formally founded in 1848 when Baron József Eötvös, Minister of Religion and Public Education donated a book in five volumes that become the first item in the inventory of the library.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Since its foundation it moved with the university from Pest to the Buda Castle in 1854 and back to Pest in 1872.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1882 it moved again, to the campus near the National Museum, now the campus of Faculty of Humanities of Eötvös Loránd University.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1909 the Library was moved to a separated cathedral like building in the new Campus of BME.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The building was designed by Samu Pécz, professor of architecture at the university.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The central Aula connects the spacious, 16.5-meter (54 ft) wide reading room to the north, the multi floor storage facility to the west and the workrooms of library procedures to the south.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The eastern facade is connected to the central building of the university with the 'Bridge of Sighs'.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The architectural concept has been proven timeless.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Later on the storage capacity was enlarged with the introduction of compact storage technology, and adding a large capacity underground storage facility under the garden of the Campus.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Today a remote storage building near Budapest is also used.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In the beginning the library was directed by university professors.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The first full-time director was appointed in 1936.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In the early years the library served only professors.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] It was opened for students in 1869, and for the general public in 1884.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In the following years extended editions of the printed catalogue were published and distributed to the departments and to other major libraries in the country.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1936 the library introduced the index card system of catalogue.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Transition to electronic cataloguing began in the 1980s, and the integrated library system was introduced in the 1990s.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] With the spreading of internet and widening the bandwidth the catalogue has become available from anywhere.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The library collection was extended by acquisitions, and with donations of professors.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] There were two major additions by receiving the heritage of baron József Eötvös in 1872, and of Károly Hieronymi engineer and politician in 1912.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] During the Second World War both the building and the collection were damaged.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Nevertheless, it continued its work in 1945, and the main reading room was reopened during the academic year of 1949–1950.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Since 1952, increasing amount of the collection has been placed on open shelves for direct access of the readers.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In the beginning only fiction, later on handbooks, and nowadays textbooks and current literature can be found on the shelves in the reading rooms.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1953 the library started publishing serials (Methodical papers of the Central Library of Budapest Technical University, publications on history of science and engineering, Scientific Technical Bibliographies) and some other serials in the 1960s.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Since the mid sixties the library takes part in the instruction of first year students with training on using the library and in teaching literature search skills.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1991 the library opened the Study of Natural Sciences with mostly chemistry-regarded literature open shelves.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The library is the centre of the library network of the university, and the thematic library in mathematics and physics.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1883 Ágoston Trefort, minister of education opened the Technological Museum including a library consisting the “basic Hungarian and international literature dealing with industry”.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1889 the library was moved and merged with the library of Public Polytechnics.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1921 the Institute of Technological and Material Testing was established, merging two institutions.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] With the integration, the Library of Technological Institute was formed.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] From 1923 the library was intensively developed by the direction of Géza Káplány.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1949 the Library of Technology was formally merged with the Technical Documentation Centre.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Since then the library started establishing liaison libraries in the country.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1952 the name changed to National Technical Library.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1956 the Library was moved into a representative building near the National Museum.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 1982 with the introduction of electronic technologies and with the development of information exchange of cooperating libraries on multinational level the library took the name of National Technical Information Centre and Library.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In 2011, following the erection of new university buildings in the new southern (Lágymányos) campus, a new service point of BME OMIKK was opened in building “I”.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Budapest University of Technology and Economics ranked 250th in mechanical engineering by QS 2017 world ranking.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] It takes the 322nd place among the world's top 400 universities for engineering and technology, being the only university from Hungary that is listed in Quacquarelli Symonds ranking.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Times Higher Education ranked it as 1001+ in its 2020 world university rankings.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Students attending the freshman camp in 2024 of the Faculty of Electrical Engineering and Informatics at the Budapest University of Technology and Economics (BME) have shared troubling accounts of the harsh treatment they experienced.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] Reports from students described an atmosphere more akin to a military boot camp, with degrading practices, body searches, and even bathroom breaks measured with stopwatches.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In Hungary, approximately one-third of students do not complete their higher education studies.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] This dropout rate is a significant concern and is influenced by a combination of factors including the competitive nature of the Hungarian education system, early selection processes, and rigid structures.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] The Hungarian education system also faces criticism for its focus on standardized testing and its impact on student well-being.
[src:donát-bánki/budapest-university-of-technology-and-economics] In the fields of IT and Physics, the dropout rate is among the highest, reaching even 50-65%, which is quite shocking.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:donát-bánki/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] In 1898, Donát Bánki invented the high-compression engine with a dual carburetor, an evaporation method used ever since.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] The invention of the carburetor helped the development of automobiles, as previously no method was known to correctly mix the fuel and air for engines.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] Some sources say that the idea of the carburetor came from a flower girl.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] One evening, Bánki saw her while walking home from the Budapest Technical University.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] She was sprinkling water onto her flowers by blowing spray from her mouth.
[src:donát-bánki/donát-bánki] Bánki is also given partial credit for the invention of the crossflow turbine.
